\par First Aid: }{\fs20\cf0 You usually use first aid to save a dying character. If a charact
er has negative hit points and is losing hit points (at the rate of 1 per round, 1 per hour, or 1 per day), you can make him or her stable. A stable character regains no hit points but stops losing them.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Long-Term Care: }{\fs20\cf0 Providing long-term care means treat
ing a wounded person for a day or more. If your Heal check is successful, the patient recovers hit points or ability score points (lost to ability damage) at twice the normal rate: 2 hit points per level for a full 8 hours of rest in a day, or 4 hit point
s per level for each full day of complete rest; 2 ability score points for a full 8 hours of rest in a day, or 4 ability score points for each full day of complete rest.
\par You can tend as many as six patients at a time. You need a few items and supplies (band
ages, salves, and so on) that are easy to come by in settled lands. Giving long-term care counts as light activity for the healer. You cannot give long-term care to yourself.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Treat Wound from Caltrop, Spike Growth, or Spike Stones: }{\fs20\cf0 A creature wounded by stepping on a caltrop moves at one-half normal speed. A successful Heal check removes this movement penalty.
\par A creature wounded by a }{\i\fs20\cf0 spike growth }{\fs20\cf0 or }{\i\fs20\cf0 spike stones }{\fs20\cf0 spell must succeed on a Reflex save or take injuries that reduce his speed by one-third. Another
 character can remove this penalty by taking 10 minutes to dress the victim\rquote s injuries and succeeding on a Heal check against the spell\rquote s save DC.
\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Treat Poison: }{\fs20\cf0 To treat poison means to tend a single character who has been poisoned and who is going to take
 more damage from the poison (or suffer some other effect). Every time the poisoned character makes a saving throw against the poison, you make a Heal check. The poisoned character uses your check result or his or her saving throw, whichever is higher.

\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Treat Disease: }{\fs20\cf0 
To treat a disease means to tend a single diseased character. Every time he or she makes a saving throw against disease effects, you make a Heal check. The diseased character uses your check result or his or her saving throw, whichever is higher.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Action:}{\fs20\cf0  Providing first aid, treating a wound, or treating poison is a standard action. Treating a disease or tending a creature wounded by a }{\i\fs20\cf0 spike growth }{\fs20\cf0 or }{\i\fs20\cf0 spike stones }{\fs20\cf0 
spell takes 10 minutes of work. Providing long-term care requires 8 hours of light activity.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Try Again:}{\fs20\cf0  Varies. Generally speaking, you can\rquote t try a Heal check again without proof of the original check\rquote 
s failure. You can always retry a check to provide first aid, assuming the target of the previous attempt is still alive.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Special:}{\fs20\cf0  A character with the Self-Sufficient feat gets a +2 bonus on Heal checks.
\par A healer\rquote s kit gives you a +2 circumstance bonus on Heal checks.
