Securing a grappling hook requires a Use Rope check (DC 10, +2 for every 10 feet of distance the grappling hook is thrown, to a maximum DC of 20 at 50 feet). Failure by 4 or less indicates that the hook fails to catch and falls, al
lowing you to try again. Failure by 5 or more indicates that the grappling hook initially holds, but comes loose after 1d4 rounds of supporting weight. This check is made secretly, so that you don\rquote t know whether the rope will hold your weight.

\par }{\i\fs20\cf0 Bind a Character: }{\fs20\cf0 When you bind another character with a rope, any Escape Artist check that the bound character makes is opposed by your Use Rope check.
\par You get a +10 bonus on this check because it is easier to bind someone than to escape from bonds. You don\rquote t even make your Use Rope check until someone tries to escape.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Action:}{\fs20\cf0  Varies. Throwing a grappling hook is a standard action that provokes an attack of opportunity. Tying a knot, tying
 a special knot, or tying a rope around yourself one-handed is a full-round action that provokes an attack of opportunity. Splicing two ropes together takes 5 minutes. Binding a character takes 1 minute.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Special:}{\fs20\cf0  A silk rope gives you a +2 circumstance bonus on Use Rope checks. If you cast an }{\i\fs20\cf0 animate rope }{\fs20\cf0 
spell on a rope, you get a +2 circumstance bonus on any Use Rope checks you make when using that rope.
\par These bonuses stack.
\par If you have the Deft Hands feat, you get a +2 bonus on Use Rope checks.
\par }{\b\fs20\cf0 Synergy:}{\fs20\cf0  If you have 5 or more ranks in Use Rope, you get a +2 bonus on Climb checks made to climb a rope, a knotted rope, or a rope-and-wall combination.
\par If you have 5 or more ranks in Use Rope, you get a +2 bonus on Escape Artist checks when escaping from rope bonds.
\par If you have 5 or more ranks in Escape Artist, you get a +2 bonus on checks made to bind someone.
